Why I reject The Very Best of Christopher Cross:
- While it ticks some boxes I like (intimate close‑miked lead vocals, tasteful clean guitar fills, concise 3–5‑minute radio hooks, and controlled remastering without brittle “sparkle”), it is described as “cozy late‑night sing‑along production” with “warm analog sax.” That places it squarely in the late‑night adult‑contemporary realm rather than the punchier 70s–80s AOR I prefer as my primary interest.
- The emphasis on warmth and restrained arrangements increases the risk of the more subdued top end and lack of aggressive electric‑guitar attack that I explicitly dislike when it robs mixes of punch. Even though the remastering is controlled, the character here is deliberately cozy/analog‑warm and sax‑forward, which is less compatible with my core preference for bright top end, tight rhythm section, and layered rock harmonies.
- In short, Christopher Cross’s Very Best leans into the late‑night AC vibe (which I can appreciate secondarily) but it lacks the AOR guitar‑forward drive, layered male harmonies, song‑forward punch and collector focus that make Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 the better match for my stated priorities.

