ector‑grade remaster) has some appealing elements: dynamically preserved transients, groove‑heavy drums/bass, tasteful saturated guitar leads, tight clear midrange, and full‑length sequencing/packaging — these respond to my appreciation for nuance and good dynamics, and the collector packaging is a plus. However, it also emphasizes a “warm tape‑like tonal match” and “forward close‑mic lead vocals.” The warm/tape‑like tonal coloration risks the “murky/overly warm mastering” I dislike, and forward close‑mic vocals risk the “overly forward vocal presentations that bury immediacy” I warned against. While Candidate 1 preserves transients, its tonal warmth and vocal proximity push it toward the analog, intimate end of the spectrum that can dull the bright, punchy AOR sound I now favor.\n3) Why I chose Candidate 2 and rejected Candidate 1:\n- Alignment with primary aesthetic: My stated primary preference is polished 70s–80s AOR (Foreigner‑style). Candidate 2 is explicitly remastered for that arena‑AOR sound—tight rhythms, punchy low end, bright top‑end, dry center vocals, lush stacked harmonies, and concise single edits—so it satisfies multiple high‑priority items simultaneously. Those are not incidental similarities; they are the exact sonic and structural attributes I said I now favor.\n- Preservation of snap and clarity: Candidate 2’s “controlled compression that preserves transient snap” directly addresses my concern that remasters should keep attack and presence rather than introducing murky warmth. Candidate 1, while preserving transients, couples that with a warm tape match that risks softening the clarity and “presence” I prize.\n- Vocal presentation: I specifically prefer dry, front‑and‑center lead vocals and dislike ragged or overly forward close‑mic vocals that can feel intrusive or bury immediacy. Candidate 2’s dry center‑front vocals and narrow imaging are the ideal presentation for that preference. Candidate 1’s “forward close‑mic lead vocals” are a red flag 