essing. Lush piano/strings and organic arrangements fit my liking for controlled, tasteful strings/brass and analog textures. Tactile sequencing and wide harmonies satisfy my collector‑oriented sequencing preference. The lack of hyper‑close vocal treatment avoids the “stacked processing buries nuance” problem.\n  - Cons: emphasizes warmth over snap and uses deeper reverbs—this risks some loss of the bright, transient‑preserving top‑end and punch I prize. However, that tradeoff is less damaging than the dynamic crushing and aggressive midrange saturation present in candidate 1, because candidate 2 retains natural vocal placement and organic separation rather than uneven, processed lead presence.\n3) Decision and rationale\nI choose candidate 2. The decisive factors are that candidate 2 keeps a natural, not hyper‑close vocal presentation and offers organic arrangements, controlled lushness and thoughtful sequencing—these align with my core AOR/AC preferences for front‑center vocals, tasteful strings/piano and intact musical separation. Candidate 1, despite being collector‑grade, exhibits several deal‑breaking attributes for me: aggressive midrange saturation, stacked vocal processing that makes lead presence uneven, and louder/tightened mastering that compromises dynamics and transient snap. Those are exactly the mastering/mixing choices I dislike and which would undermine the clarity, separation and punch I care about. While candidate 2 leans warmer and uses deeper reverbs (a potential softening of snap), it avoids the harsher faults of candidate 1 and therefore better preserves nuance, natural vocal presence and the lush but controlled AOR feel I prefer.'. \n\n However, upon actually listening to these two CDs, you discovered that you don't like the CD that you initially chose ('Greatest Hits'). Instead, you prefer the CD that you did not choose before ('Journey: Greatest Hits').\n This indicates that you made an incorrect choice, and your judgment about your prefer